						               													<description>Slacking isn't just a pastime, it's a calling. Four Day Weekend players build card sets detailing the true art of avoiding work. Each set must show a (not very) plausible reason for missing work, the real activity the slacker is pursuing, and one to four methods of attaining the necessities for survival while not working: food, cash, shelter, and transportation.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players begin each turn with up to five cards in hand, discarding and replenishing before actually playing cards into sets. The discards are placed in front of the player - replenishment cards can be taken from the draw pile or from other players' discard rows. Once the player has five cards, he/she creates and adds to sets.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Points for sets are calculated from base card values, card combination multipliers, and bonus card conditions.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;For example, the player might start a new set with the &amp;quot;Fell Off The Roof Again&amp;quot; Excuse. She adds the &amp;quot;Building a Couch Fort&amp;quot; Activity and the &amp;quot;Van Full of Nuns&amp;quot; Transportation card she picked up from another player's discard pile.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each round ends when at least three complete sets have been created and a player declares &amp;quot;Back to Work-ish.&amp;quot; Total up the sets, and the slacker with the most points wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
